.TH HSH 1 "April 2026" "Holberton School" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
hsh \- simple UNIX command interpreter
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B hsh
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hsh
is a simple command line interpreter.

It displays a prompt in interactive mode, reads one command line,
splits it into arguments on spaces and tabs, creates a child process
with
.BR fork (2),
executes the command with
.BR execve (2),
and waits for the command to finish.

This version supports commands given as absolute paths or found through
.BR PATH ,
with arguments separated by spaces and tabs.

It also works in non-interactive mode, for example when input is piped
from another command or from a file.

.SH FEATURES
.TP
Prompt
Displays
.B ($)
when standard input is a terminal.
.TP
Command execution
Executes one command at a time using
.BR execve (2).
.TP
Arguments
Splits the input line on spaces and tabs and passes the resulting
arguments to
.BR execve (2).
.TP
PATH lookup
Searches executable files in
.B PATH
before calling
.BR fork (2),
so no child is created when a command does not exist.
.TP
Built-in commands
Implements
.B exit
to leave the shell and
.B env
to print the current environment.
.TP
Process handling
Creates a child process and waits for it with
.BR waitpid (2).
.TP
End of file
Exits cleanly on
.B Ctrl+D
in interactive mode.

.SH LIMITATIONS
This version does not:
.TP
Handle advanced shell syntax
No pipes, redirections, semicolons, quotes, or wildcards.
.TP
Handle arguments for exit
Only
.B exit
without arguments is required in this version.
.TP
Modify the environment
Built-ins such as
.B setenv
and
.B unsetenv
are not implemented.

.SH RETURN VALUE
Returns the exit status of the last executed command.

.SH EXAMPLES
Interactive mode:
.PP
.nf
$ ./hsh
($) env
USER=julien
HOME=/home/julien
PATH=/usr/local/sbin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/sbin:/usr/bin:/sbin:/bin
($) exit
$
.fi

Non-interactive mode:
.PP
.nf
$ echo "env" | ./hsh
USER=julien
HOME=/home/julien
PATH=/usr/local/sbin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/sbin:/usr/bin:/sbin:/bin
.fi

